               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1353" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1353" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1353" type="surname" value="BRASLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1353" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH BRASLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am fourteen years old. Emma Brasley was my sister—she was two years and six months old—I was with her in the yard behind the house, between one and two o'clock one day, standing by her side, and the prisoner, who lived in the same house, threw some hot water out of the window, which came partly on my sister—she fell down—I picked her up directly, and she was taken in doors—I had seen the win<lb></lb>dow opened a few minutes before the water was thrown out, and I had seen the prisoner at the window about a quarter of an hour before—my sister was taken to the hospital the same afternoon—the prisoner came down stairs crying, and said she was very sorry for what had happened.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1354" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1354" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1354" type="surname" value="JOY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1354" type="given" value="CHARLOTTE"></interp>CHARLOTTE JOY</persName>
                  </hi>. I saw the child directly after it was scalded, and assisted the mother in taking her clothes off—the skin came off with the clothes—the prisoner seemed very much troubled and sorry for what she had done.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1355" type="witnessName">
